<paragraph id="BD1736D1FFAF2A7D84ADFE0EFEFF61E9" blockId="3.[151,603,361,424]" box="[151,365,397,424]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
(
<figureCitation id="25932A54FFAF2A7D84A5FE0EFE8061E6" box="[159,274,397,423]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1955,1979]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetId="figure-98@4.[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Hydatothrips bahaensis sp. n. female. (8) Head and pronotum; (9) Metasternal plate; (10) Meso- and metanotum; (11) Tergites IV–VI; (12) Sternites IV–VI; (13) Tergites VII–X; (14) Fore wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4435714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4435714/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Figs 8–14</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="25932A54FFAF2A7D8524FE0EFEF761E9" box="[286,357,397,424]" captionStart="FIGURES 32–35" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1748,1772]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,181,1724]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[151,1435,181,1724]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 32–35. Adult habitus of Hydatothrips spp.: (32, 33) adolfifriderici (Female and male respectively); (34, 35) bahaensis sp. n. (Female and male respectively)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4435724" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4435724/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">34, 35</figureCitation>
)
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BD1736D1FFAF2A7D84ADFE53FAAF6447" blockId="3.[151,1437,464,2039]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="8FDCEAC3FFAF2A7D84ADFE53FEEA61AB" box="[151,376,464,490]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Female macroptera</emphasis>
. Body reddish brown (
<figureCitation id="25932A54FFAF2A7D86BDFE53FD4C61AB" box="[647,734,464,490]" captionStart="FIGURES 32–35" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1748,1772]" captionTargetBox="[151,1433,181,1724]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[151,1435,181,1724]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 32–35. Adult habitus of Hydatothrips spp.: (32, 33) adolfifriderici (Female and male respectively); (34, 35) bahaensis sp. n. (Female and male respectively)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4435724" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4435724/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
); antennal segments I–IV yellow, IV brown at apex, V–VIII brown; head, pronotum, pterothorax and abdominal segments I–VII reddish brown; meso and metasternal plates, abdominal VIII–X and legs dark brown; fore wing brown with sub basal band paler (
<figureCitation id="25932A54FFAF2A7D8051FD9BFB526273" box="[1131,1216,536,562]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1955,1979]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetId="figure-98@4.[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Hydatothrips bahaensis sp. n. female. (8) Head and pronotum; (9) Metasternal plate; (10) Meso- and metanotum; (11) Tergites IV–VI; (12) Sternites IV–VI; (13) Tergites VII–X; (14) Fore wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4435714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4435714/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
); clavus brown but pale at extreme apex. Head with occipital apodeme touching posterior margin of eyes and ocellar triangle; ocellar triangle with irregular widely spaced transverse striae, with longitudinal lines of internal markings; setae pair III arise inside ocellar triangle (
<figureCitation id="25932A54FFAF2A7D85EEFD07FD8A62DF" box="[468,536,644,670]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1955,1979]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetId="figure-98@4.[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Hydatothrips bahaensis sp. n. female. (8) Head and pronotum; (9) Metasternal plate; (10) Meso- and metanotum; (11) Tergites IV–VI; (12) Sternites IV–VI; (13) Tergites VII–X; (14) Fore wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4435714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4435714/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). Antenna 8-segmented. Pronotum with one pair of minute posteroangular setae, transversely reticulate, with internal markings in reticles, pronotal blotch transversely reticulate, with internal longitudinal lines (
<figureCitation id="25932A54FFAF2A7D857FFD4FFE1A62A7" box="[325,392,716,742]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1955,1979]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetId="figure-98@4.[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Hydatothrips bahaensis sp. n. female. (8) Head and pronotum; (9) Metasternal plate; (10) Meso- and metanotum; (11) Tergites IV–VI; (12) Sternites IV–VI; (13) Tergites VII–X; (14) Fore wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4435714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4435714/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
); mesonotum transversely striate, with irregular internal markings; metanotum longitudinally reticulate, with internal markings, median and sub median setal pairs arising at anterior margin (
<figureCitation id="25932A54FFAF2A7D80E1FD73FABD634B" box="[1243,1327,752,778]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1955,1979]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetId="figure-98@4.[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Hydatothrips bahaensis sp. n. female. (8) Head and pronotum; (9) Metasternal plate; (10) Meso- and metanotum; (11) Tergites IV–VI; (12) Sternites IV–VI; (13) Tergites VII–X; (14) Fore wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4435714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4435714/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
); anterior margin of metasternal plate deeply emarginate (
<figureCitation id="25932A54FFAF2A7D8689FC97FD6A636F" box="[691,760,788,814]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1955,1979]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetId="figure-98@4.[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Hydatothrips bahaensis sp. n. female. (8) Head and pronotum; (9) Metasternal plate; (10) Meso- and metanotum; (11) Tergites IV–VI; (12) Sternites IV–VI; (13) Tergites VII–X; (14) Fore wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4435714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4435714/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); fore wing with sub basal band longer than wide (
<figureCitation id="25932A54FFAF2A7D8101FC97FA1C636F" box="[1339,1422,788,814]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1955,1979]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetId="figure-98@4.[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Hydatothrips bahaensis sp. n. female. (8) Head and pronotum; (9) Metasternal plate; (10) Meso- and metanotum; (11) Tergites IV–VI; (12) Sternites IV–VI; (13) Tergites VII–X; (14) Fore wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4435714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4435714/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
), second vein without setae (
<figureCitation id="25932A54FFAF2A7D85F3FCBBFD8F6313" box="[457,541,824,850]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1955,1979]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetId="figure-98@4.[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Hydatothrips bahaensis sp. n. female. (8) Head and pronotum; (9) Metasternal plate; (10) Meso- and metanotum; (11) Tergites IV–VI; (12) Sternites IV–VI; (13) Tergites VII–X; (14) Fore wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4435714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4435714/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). Tergites I–VIII with rows of dense microtrichia laterally; tergites III–VII with microtrichia medially; tergites III–VI with setae S3 arising well ahead of posterior margin, with 6–8 further setae lateral to S3 (
<figureCitation id="25932A54FFAF2A7D8516FC03FEEE63DB" box="[300,380,896,922]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1955,1979]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetId="figure-98@4.[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Hydatothrips bahaensis sp. n. female. (8) Head and pronotum; (9) Metasternal plate; (10) Meso- and metanotum; (11) Tergites IV–VI; (12) Sternites IV–VI; (13) Tergites VII–X; (14) Fore wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4435714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4435714/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
); tergites II–V without posteromarginal microtrichia medially; tergites VII–VIII with complete comb of microtrichia; tergite IX with 2 pairs of mid-dorsal setae (
<figureCitation id="25932A54FFAF2A7D8743FC27FC5E63FF" box="[889,972,932,958]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1955,1979]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetId="figure-98@4.[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Hydatothrips bahaensis sp. n. female. (8) Head and pronotum; (9) Metasternal plate; (10) Meso- and metanotum; (11) Tergites IV–VI; (12) Sternites IV–VI; (13) Tergites VII–X; (14) Fore wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4435714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4435714/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
); tergite X with few microtrichia posteriorly and without median split; sternites III–VI completely covered with microtrichia medially, posterior margin with comb of microtrichia medially (
<figureCitation id="25932A54FFAF2A7D85C6FC6FFDDD6447" box="[508,591,1004,1030]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–14" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1955,1979]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetId="figure-98@4.[151,1435,309,1931]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 8–14. Hydatothrips bahaensis sp. n. female. (8) Head and pronotum; (9) Metasternal plate; (10) Meso- and metanotum; (11) Tergites IV–VI; (12) Sternites IV–VI; (13) Tergites VII–X; (14) Fore wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4435714" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4435714/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
); posterior setae at sternite VII arising in front of posterior margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BD1736D1FFAF2A7D84FDFB93FBC46432" blockId="3.[151,1437,464,2039]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="8FDCEAC3FFAF2A7D84FDFB93FEE4646B" bold="true" box="[199,374,1040,1066]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Measurements</emphasis>
(
<typeStatus id="62138873FFAF2A7D85B3FB93FE7F646B" box="[393,493,1040,1066]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">holotype</typeStatus>
Female): Body length 1250; Head length 105, width 180; pronotum length 120, width 225; ovipositor length 230; ocellar setae pair III 14; metanotum median setae 26; fore wing length 775; antennal segments I–VIII 25, 35, 62, 60, 50, 60, 15, 15 respectively; tergite IX S1 setae 57.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BD1736D1FFAF2A7D84FDFBFFFDC36542" blockId="3.[151,1437,464,2039]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
Female 
<typeStatus id="62138873FFAF2A7D8518FBFEFE0064D6" box="[290,402,1149,1175]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">paratypes</typeStatus>
: Body length 1142–1250; Head length 95–105, width 174–180; pronotum length 110–120, width 220–225; ovipositor length 220–230; ocellar setae pair III 12–14; metanotum median setae 24–26; fore wing wing length 763–775; antennal segments I–VIII length 23–25, 32–35, 57–62, 55–60, 46–50, 55–60, 12–15, 12–15 respectively; tergite IX S1 setae 55–57.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BD1736D1FFAF2A7D84FDFA8FFABA6567" blockId="3.[151,1437,464,2039]" box="[199,1320,1292,1319]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="8FDCEAC3FFAF2A7D84FDFA8FFE186567" box="[199,394,1292,1318]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Male macroptera</emphasis>
. Similar to female, but smaller in size; sternites VI–VII with transverse pore plate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BD1736D1FFAF2A7D84FDFAB3FC8E65D2" blockId="3.[151,1437,464,2039]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="8FDCEAC3FFAF2A7D84FDFAB3FEE4650B" bold="true" box="[199,374,1328,1354]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Measurements</emphasis>
(male 
<typeStatus id="62138873FFAF2A7D85F8FAB2FDBA650A" box="[450,552,1329,1355]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">paratype</typeStatus>
): Body length 900; head length 75, width 145; pronotum length 145, width 175; ocellar setae pair III 10; metanotum median setae 23; fore wing length 580; antennal segments I–VIII length 20, 35, 50, 45, 45, 50, 14, 14 respectively; tergite IX S1 setae 50.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="BD1736D1FFAF2A7D84FDFA1EFB866662" blockId="3.[151,1437,464,2039]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="8FDCEAC3FFAF2A7D84FDFA1EFEA265F7" box="[199,304,1437,1462]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Larvae II</emphasis>
. Body yellowish (
<figureCitation id="25932A54FFAF2A7D85C0FA1FFDDC65F7" box="[506,590,1436,1462]" captionStart="FIGURES 36–40" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1460,1484]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,185,1436]" captionTargetId="figure-21@10.[151,1435,181,1436]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 36–40. Adult and larval Sericothripinae: (36, 37) N. amygdali (Female and male respectively); (38) N. samayunkur (Female). (39) H. bahaensis sp. n. larva. (40) N. amygdali larva." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4435726" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4435726/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
); antennae, coxae, outer margin of all tibiae and abdominal segment IX with gray; antennae 7-segmented; pterothorax with three lateral dark spots, which are absent on pronotum. Major body setae brown with broadly expanded apex (about three times as wide as base) arising from brown ring. Length of setae 15–20 excluding basal ring, width at apex 12–15, width at base of setae 5.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
